# Service Layer Guidelines

## Core Principles
- Services contain **all business logic** — the brain of the application
- Services orchestrate: call repositories for data, call clients for external data, apply business rules
- Controllers never call repositories or clients directly — always through services
- One service can call another, but avoid circular dependencies

## `@Transactional` Best Practices
- Use `@Transactional` at **method level**, not class level
- Use `@Transactional(readOnly = true)` for read-only operations — Hibernate skips dirty checks
- Default propagation (`REQUIRED`) is fine for most cases
- Never put `@Transactional` on `private` methods — Spring proxies can't intercept them

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class PreShiftCheckService {
    private final PreShiftCheckRepository preShiftCheckRepository;
    private final PreShiftCheckMapper preShiftCheckMapper;

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public PreShiftCheckResponseDto getById(Long id) {
        PreShiftCheck entity = preShiftCheckRepository.findById(id)
                .orElseThrow(() -> new ResourceNotFoundException("Pre-shift check not found: " + id));
        return preShiftCheckMapper.toDto(entity);
    }

    @Transactional
    public PreShiftCheckResponseDto create(CreatePreShiftCheckRequest request) {
        PreShiftCheck entity = preShiftCheckMapper.toEntity(request);
        PreShiftCheck saved = preShiftCheckRepository.save(entity);
        return preShiftCheckMapper.toDto(saved);
    }
}
```

## Exception Throwing Guide
- `ResourceNotFoundException` — entity not found by ID or unique key
- `BadRequestException` — input passes validation but fails business rules
- `ConflictException` — duplicate resource or state conflict
- Let `ExternalServiceException` bubble up from clients unless handling partial failures

## What Does NOT Belong in Services
- HTTP-specific concerns (`HttpStatus`, `ResponseEntity`, `HttpServletRequest`)
- Direct JSON parsing or serialization
- Logging request/response payloads (that's the filter's job)
